The paper deals with finding correspondences between shapes, which is a common problem in computer vision and graphics. The use of simplified shape graphs and graph matching techniques suggests that the paper may belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) or graphics (cs.GR) sub-categories. The fact that the method is applicable across multiple shape representations suggests that it may also belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) sub-category. The use of feature points and point-to-point maps suggests that the paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the emphasis on robustness and efficiency suggests that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
